body: I wonder if this could also somehow be related to https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/issues/10104.

Right. It doesn't work in that way. Do you know if Linux has an API to get known if the available CPUs were restricted to a subset? 
And I suggest we add an SessionOption for thread affinity, and turn if off by default.

> Do you know if Linux has an API to get known if the available CPUs were restricted to a subset?

There's [pthread_getaffinity_np](https://www.man7.org/linux/man-pages/man3/pthread_setaffinity_np.3.html) and the pseudo-filesystem [/dev/cpuset](https://www.man7.org/linux/man-pages/man7/cpuset.7.html).

In particular:
> In addition to the above pseudo-files in each directory below /dev/cpuset, each process has a pseudo-file, /proc/\<pid\>/cpuset, that displays the path of the process's cpuset directory relative  to the root of the cpuset filesystem.
> 
> Also the /proc/\<pid\>/status file for each process has four added lines, displaying the process's Cpus_allowed (on which CPUs it may be scheduled

issue.body:
**Description**:
This checks the size of the `ThreadOptions.affinity` vector to be either zero or match the number of threads in the thread pool. The thread pool implementations in `onnxruntime/core/platform/windows/env.cc` and `onnxruntime/core/platform/posix/env.cc` depend on the correct size:

https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/blob/05d20343ee04990a7082ccb162faab9dd9a8305c/onnxruntime/core/platform/windows/env.cc#L103

and 

https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/blob/05d20343ee04990a7082ccb162faab9dd9a8305c/onnxruntime/core/platform/posix/env.cc#L179

**Motivation and Context**
Might fix https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/issues/10113.

body: @henrywu2019 I think onnxruntime currently does not check for the correct size of the affinity vector. It assumes to have at least as many entries as threads in the thread pool. I have proposed an additional check in https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/pull/10122. Could this maybe be the reason for the crash you are experiencing?
When you use cpuset with onnxruntime, you can't use onnxruntime's default session options. You need to explicitly tell onnxruntime how many threads it should create.
Can you give me some workable sample code? Thanks! @snnn

Please set this property: https://onnxruntime.ai/docs/api/python/api_summary.html#onnxruntime.SessionOptions.intra_op_num_threads 

Default is 0 to let onnxruntime choose. But in this case, onnxruntime doesn't do it correctly.
set it equal to the number of the really available cores?

issue.title: LCBench fails on cluster
issue.body:
Had to manually roll back a library to get LCBench from YAHPO to run on the cluster, though it worked fine locally. 

Went with this comment [here](https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/issues/10113#issuecomment-999496216) as a solution.

**Why manual?**
`poetry add onnxruntime==1.6.0` fails due to `yahpo-gym`'s dependency on `onnxruntime (>=1.10.0)`.

**Fix**:
`pip install onnxruntime==1.6.0`

**How to check?**
`just run asha lcbench_7593` should work.
